In the quest of(parasites) organisms which live in or on the body of other organisms, obtain nourishment and finally cause harm to the second organisms(hosts), they face certain challenges . These challenges are considered the inhibitors of the expressionof the full potential of parasites.  Given that parasites interact at close range with the hosts, hosts deploy mechanisms such as immune suppression or attacks or behaviorally choosing a site to live or being active at certain times of the day and season to avoid parasites. Both the parasitesand hosts play rital roles in their environment to ensure their continuous survival. Let elaborate four challenges parasites face in their quest to inhabit a biotic environment. First suppression or attacks by the host's immune system, then difficulty in obtaining the required nourishment due to less developed digestive system, inability of parasites to complete their their life cycle and variation in matching of host and parasite genomes.Most living species are parasitic. Hosts in turn deploy their immune systems to prevent infections or keep the parasites in check . The immune systemis one of the most complex systems and shows many signs of coevolution with parasites . The immune system is well tuned to it's task , as long lived multicellular organisms would probably not be able to survive and outpace their short-lived and numerous parasites. Nonetheless, immune responses vary among host's life cycle or infection by different parasite types. For instance, a host may be killed before the full potential of transmission will be exploited.Again, most parasites due to their less elaborate digestive systems, lack adequate nourishment from the host organism. This food aquisition is by permeable tegument for active absorption and possesses muscular pharynx. These parasites due to this, depend on predigested food from host. Where in the absence of host nutrition, parasites cannot obtain nourishment from other sources.Parasites are faced with the challenge of variationin host and parasite genomes. In that only some parasite genotypes are able to infect a particular host genotype, and vice versa,only some host genotypes are able to resist a particular set of parasite genotypes. This means that not all parasites can infect all hosts and not all hosts can resist all parasites. Some hosts have mechanisms to counter the effect of some parasites and some parasites have mechanisms to outpace the resistance of hosts.Finally, inability of parasites to complete their life cycle due to the heteroxenous nature of development affects their continuous survival. Some parasites require more than one host to complete it's lifecycle, hence if the host is killed whilst containing the parasites, then the life cycle will not be complete since it requires a definitive host to complete it's life cycle. For example, the life cycle of taenia solium begins from an infected human, to pigs to pig's intestinesand then back to humans. Here if the pig gets killed the parasite wouldn't achieve it's full potential on the host by it's inability to complete it's life cycle.
